<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>Things to do:</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>Track brown bears in the ABC Islands.</li><li>Sea kayak to a tidewater glacier.</li><li>Wild camp beneath North America's highest mountain.</li><li>Whale and orca watch on a Glacier Bay cruise.</li><li>Ride a gold rush-era train to the Yukon.</li><li>Spot salmon-guzzling brown bears at Brooks Falls.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>Things to Remember</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":5} -->
<h5>Alaska Weather</h5>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Alaskan weather is quite unpredictable. It could be a clear bright day then in an instance you'll be in the middle of a snow storm. Make sure you bring warm clothing and a decent pair of shoes. In the months of June and July they are usually fine for sun and bright days the rest of the year remember the warm clothes.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":5} -->
<h5>Wild Life (bear safety)</h5>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":128,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://localhost/AlaskaCo/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Bear-safety.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-128"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Know the difference between black and brown bears.&nbsp;Both black bears and brown or grizzly bears live in areas where there are state parks. Use more than the fur color for identification. There are cinnamon black bears and black brown bears.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you are traveling with a dog make sure to keep them on a leash. As instances of dogs off leash have been known to bring bears back to their owners.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Some good habits when traveling the wilderness:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>Make plenty of noise (Of course within reason). Surprising a bear will be worse than letting them know you are around.</li><li>Travel the Alaskan wilderness in a group.</li><li>If camping make sure to put away all food and leave no rubbish. Also if cooking, cook away from the camp.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Incase of a face to face encounter. STAY CALM. Attacks are rare. Bears may approach or stand on their hind legs to get a better look at you. These are curious, not aggressive, bears. Stand tall, wave your arms, and speak in a loud and low voice. DO NOT RUN! Stand your ground or back away slowly and diagonally. If the bear follows, STOP.</p>
